<h2>An Irenic Conclusion</h2>

<p>The Union of Brest was not a simple event with simple morals. The bishops who chose Rome were not traitors. The bishops who refused were not reactionaries. Both were trying to preserve the faith and protect their people in an impossible situation.</p>

<p>The lesson of Brest is not about which side was right. It is about the cost of division. When the Body of Christ is fractured, every attempt to mend it creates new fractures. The only way forward is the hard, slow, patient work of dialogue, mutual respect, and shared prayer.</p>

<p>The Greek-Catholic tradition at its best holds a profound hope: that East and West can coexist within one communion, each enriching the other, neither absorbing the other. Whether that hope is realistic remains to be seen. That it is worth pursuing seems beyond question.</p>

<h2>Further Reading</h2>

<p>Borys Gudziak's <em>Crisis and Reform: The Kyivan Metropolitanate, the Patriarchate of Constantinople, and the Genesis of the Union of Brest</em> is the definitive academic study of the Union's origins. For the Soviet persecution, see Serge Keleher's <em>Passion and Resurrection: The Greek Catholic Church in Soviet Ukraine</em>. The catechism <em>Christ Our Pascha</em>, published by the UGCC, provides the Church's own self-understanding. Kallistos Ware's <em>The Orthodox Church</em> gives the Orthodox perspective on the Union.</p>

